'''Jack William Hendry''' (born 7 May 1995) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al-Ettifaq FC|Al-Ettifaq]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

He has previously played for [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[K.V. Oostende|KV Oostende]]. He has also had loan spells at [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]], [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]], [[A-League]] club [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] and [[Serie A]] club [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]].

==Early life==
Hendry was born in Glasgow.<ref name=Soccerway/> He had spells as a youth player with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]]. He joined [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on trial in 2013 and subsequently signed a contract with them, but his time there was severely disrupted by a bout of [[Infectious mononucleosis|glandular fever]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Temple |first1=Alan |title=Former Dundee star Jack Hendry reveals how glandular fever ordeal wrecked Dundee United stint |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-united/2445160/former-dundee-star-jack-hendry-reveals-how-glandular-fever-ordeal-wrecked-dundee-united-stint/ |access-date=24 September 2022 |work=The Courier |date=10 August 2021 |location=Dundee}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Partick Thistle===
Hendry joined Partick Thistle in August 2014. He featured in Thistle's development squad frequently, before making his first-team debut for the side on the final day of the [[2014–15 in Scottish football|2014–15 season]] in a goalless draw against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] at [[Fir Park]] on 23 May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=McLauchlin|first=Brian|date=23 May 2015|title=Motherwell 0-0 Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32664221|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=1 June 2015}}</ref>

On 2 June 2015, Hendry signed a new one-year contract with the Jags, alongside [[David Wilson (footballer, born 1994)|David Wilson]] and goalkeepers [[Paul Gallacher]] and [[Tomáš Černý]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Czech bounces into Firhill|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2015-2016/june_2015/czech_bounces_into_firhill|publisher=Partick Thistle FC|access-date=2 June 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222114809/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2015-2016/june_2015/czech_bounces_into_firhill|archive-date=22 December 2015}}</ref> After an outstanding pre season, Hendry came on as a substitute in the opening game of the season away to [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]] after only 29 minutes following an earlier red card for [[Frédéric Frans]], he went on to help keep a clean sheet alongside [[Liam Lindsay]] in defence as the match finished 0–0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton 0-0 Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33662248|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Sutherland|first=Jonathan|date=1 August 2015|access-date=3 August 2015}}</ref> Following the match it was reported that English [[Premier League]] club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] had been watching Hendry.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton eye Jags star Hendry|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/13526187.Everton_eye_Jags_star_Hendry/|publisher=Newsquest Herald & Times Group|work=Evening Times|last=Jack|first=Christopher|date=3 August 2015|access-date=3 August 2015}}</ref>

===Wigan Athletic===
On 1 September 2015, Hendry signed for [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34122239 |title=Wigan Athletic: Kellett, Vuckic & Hendry sign |publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 September 2015 |access-date=1 September 2015}}</ref> He joined fellow [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on loan until the end of the season in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35884016|title=Wigan Athletic: Shrewsbury Town sign defender Jack Hendry on loan|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 March 2016|access-date=23 March 2016}}</ref>

On 31 August 2016, Hendry joined League One side [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] on loan until January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wiganathletic.com/news/2016/august/jack-hendry-joins-mk-dons-on-loan/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211214205915/https://wiganathletic.com/news/2016/august/jack-hendry-joins-mk-dons-on-loan/ |archive-date=14 December 2021 |title=Jack Hendry Joins MK Dons on Loan |publisher=Wigan Athletic FC |date=31 August 2016 |access-date=14 December 2021}}</ref> On 4 October 2016, Hendry made his debut for Milton Keynes Dons, featuring in a 0–1 away [[EFL Trophy]] group stage win over [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mkdons.com/news/article/2016-17/report-peterborough-united-0-1-mk-dons-3346966.aspx |title=Report: Peterborough United 0-1 MK Dons |publisher=MK Dons FC |date=4 October 2016 |access-date=4 October 2016}}</ref>

===Dundee===
Hendry signed a two-year contract with [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] in July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40511738 |title=Jack Hendry: Dundee recruit centre-half on two-year deal |publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 July 2017 |access-date=5 July 2017}}</ref> He played regularly and became a key player for Dundee in the first part of the 2017–18 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-fc/558643/analysis-dundee-summers-signings-hits-misses-maybes/ |title=Analysis: Dundee summers signings – the hits, misses and maybes |first=Neil |last=Robertson |work=The Courier |publisher=DC Thomson |date=6 December 2017 |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref> Dundee rejected offers from [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] for Hendry during January 2018,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-fc/587933/dundee-boss-neil-mccann-happy-reject-low-bid-jack-hendry/ |title=Dundee boss Neil McCann happy to reject 'very low' bid for Jack Hendry |first=Ian |last=Roache |work=The Courier |publisher=DC Thomson |date=27 January 2018 |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref> before agreeing a club-record fee on 31 January.<ref name = "celtic"/>

===Celtic===
[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] signed Hendry to a four-and-a-half-year contract on 31 January 2018.<ref name = "celtic">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42890313 |title=Celtic sign Dundee's Jack Hendry & Scott Bain; Scott Allan joins Hibs|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |date=1 February 2018|access-date=1 February 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 1–0 defeat away to [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] on 3 February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/brendan-rodgers-backs-jack-hendry-to-settle-after-tough-celtic-debut-1-4682343 |title=Brendan Rodgers backs Jack Hendry to settle after tough Celtic debut |publisher=JPI Media|work=The Scotsman|date=4 February 2018 |access-date=19 March 2018|first=Craig|last=Forbes}}</ref>

====Melbourne City====
On 22 January 2020, Hendry joined [[A-League]] club [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] on loan for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/a-league/melbourne-city-bring-in-defensive-recruit-jack-hendry-to-cover-for-longterm-loss-of-richard-windbichler/news-story/846469b0344a3de4003c7b8bf58c5af9 |title=Melbourne City bring in defensive recruit Jack Hendry to cover for long-term loss of Richard Windbichler |last=Davutovic |first=David |date=22 January 2020 |work=Herald Sun |url-access=subscription|access-date=22 January 2020|quote=Former Celtic defender Jack Hendry could make his Melbourne City debut in Saturday's battle for second against Perth Glory at AAMI Park after signing on loan.}}</ref> During his second appearance for Melbourne, Hendry suffered a knee ligament injury that required surgery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51372387 |title=Jack Hendry: Celtic defender faces surgery after injury at Melbourne City |publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2020 |access-date=4 February 2020}}</ref>

===Oostende===
Hendry was loaned to Belgian club [[K.V. Oostende|KV Oostende]] in July 2020,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53411596 |title=Jack Hendry: Celtic defender joins KV Oostende on loan |publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 July 2020 |access-date=14 July 2020}}</ref> and Celtic gave the Belgian club first option to buy him.<ref name = euros>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57299628 |title=Jack Hendry: Celtic centre-half's future uncertain after Oostende loan ahead of Euros |website=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2021 |accessdate=31 May 2021}}</ref> In his [[Belgian First Division A|Belgian Pro League]] debut in September 2020 he scored a last-minute winner against [[K.V. Mechelen|KV Mechelen]] to clinch a 1–0 victory for his new club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jack-hendry-admits-relief-celtic-22677956|access-date=14 September 2020|work=Daily Record|title=Jack Hendry admits relief as Celtic loanee opens up on ending his 'hell' with debut winner|first=Mark|last=Walker|date=14 September 2020|publisher=Reach Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/belgian-teenager-vranckx-responds-after-shocking-miss-goes/1ptr2ecd4a3jo1fwl74b72rbr4|work=Goal.com|access-date=14 September 2020|first=Josh|last=Thomas|title=Belgian teenager Vranckx responds after shocking miss goes viral|date=13 September 2020}}</ref> At the end of the regular season, Hendry was named as the highest-rated player in the division by {{interlanguage link|Sport/Voetbalmagazine|nl}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/19245953.celtics-jack-hendry-named-best-player-belgian-pro-league-future-remains-uncertain/|title=Celtic's Jack Hendry named best player in Belgian Pro League as future remains uncertain|website=Glasgow Times|date=20 April 2021|accessdate=4 June 2021}}</ref> Hendry moved to Oostende on a permanent basis in June 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57623531 |title=Jack Hendry: Celtic sell centre-half to Oostende after loan season in Belgium |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=26 June 2021 |access-date=26 June 2021}}</ref>

===Club Brugge===
On 31 August 2021, just two-months after signing permanently for KV Oostende, Hendry joined [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]] on a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=JACK HENDRY NAAR CLUB BRUGGE |url=https://www.clubbrugge.be/nl/nieuws/jack-hendry-naar-club-brugge |website=clubbrugge.be/ |publisher=Club Brugge KV |access-date=1 September 2021 |language=Dutch |date=31 August 2021}}</ref> He featured in Brugge's famous 1–1 Champions League draw against a star-studded [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|PSG]] side (featuring [[Lionel Messi|Messi]], [[Kylian Mbappe|Mbappé]] and [[Neymar]] playing together for the first time), and was named as Player of the Match by the BBC.<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Bruges 1-1 Paris Saint-Germain |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58577370 |publisher=BBC Sport |last=Bysouth |first=Alex |date=2021-09-15 |access-date=2021-09-17}}</ref> Hendry would score his first goal for the side in a win over [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] in a game which clinched Club Brugge the [[Jupiler pro league|Jupiler Pro League]] title.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Club Brugge win Belgian league title |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/club-brugge-win-belgian-league-title/2588841 |access-date=2022-05-15 |website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Pilcher |first=Ross |date=2022-05-15 |title=Jack Hendry replicates Celtic champion feeling as Club Brugge title triumph |url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/other-football/jack-hendry-replicates-celtic-champion-23966343 |access-date=2022-05-15 |website=footballscotland |language=en}}</ref>

====Loan to Cremonese====
On 1 September 2022, Hendry joined [[U.S. Cremonese|Cremonese]] in Italy on loan, with an option to buy.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Cremonese|url=https://www.uscremonese.it/hendry-nuovo-calciatore-della-cremonese/|title=HENDRY NUOVO CALCIATORE DELLA CREMONESE|date=1 September 2022|access-date=1 September 2022|language=it|archive-date=3 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230203194655/https://www.uscremonese.it/hendry-nuovo-calciatore-della-cremonese/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hendry made his debut for Cremonese in a [[Serie A]] game against [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hanratty |first=Robbie |date=2022-09-11 |title=Jack Hendry makes Serie A debut as Cremonese dent Atalanta's title hopes |url=https://www.footballscotland.co.uk/spfl/scottish-premiership/jack-hendry-makes-serie-debut-24990630 |access-date=2022-09-12 |website=footballscotland |language=en}}</ref> On 26 January 2023, Hendry would return to his parent club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-26 |title=Jack Hendry terug naar Club Brugge |url=https://www.clubbrugge.be/nl/nieuws/jack-hendry-terug-naar-club-brugge |access-date=2023-01-26 |website=Club Brugge |language=nl}}</ref>

===Al-Ettifaq===
On 26 July 2023, Hendry signed for Saudi club [[Al-Ettifaq FC|Al-Ettifaq]] until 2026, along with his former teammate at Celtic, [[Moussa Dembélé (French footballer)|Moussa Dembélé]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66320486|title=Jack Hendry: Scotland centre-half joins Saudi side Al-Ettifaq|website=BBC Sport|date=26 July 2023}}</ref>

==International career==
In March 2018, Hendry received his first call-up to the [[Scotland national football team|senior Scotland squad]] for the [[Exhibition game#International football|friendlies]] with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12017/11296201/kieran-tierney-and-russell-martin-to-miss-scotland-friendlies-jack-hendry-receives-call-up |title=Kieran Tierney and Russell Martin to miss Scotland friendlies; Jack Hendry receives call-up |publisher=Sky Sports|date=18 March 2018 |access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref> He made his Scotland debut on 27 March, playing in a 1–0 win against Hungary.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43563840 |title=Hungary 0–1 Scotland: Alex McLeish praises 'amazing' Scott McKenna & Jack Hendry |publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 March 2018 |access-date=28 March 2018}}</ref> Hendry was recalled to the squad in March 2021, after performing well in the Belgian league for [[K.V. Oostende|KV Oostende]].<ref name = euros/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/19163695.scotland-squad-steve-clarke-calls-che-adams-jack-hendry-world-cup-qualifiers/ |title=Scotland squad: Steve Clarke calls up Che Adams and Jack Hendry for World Cup qualifiers |first=Aidan |last=Smith |newspaper=Glasgow Times |date=16 March 2021 |accessdate=17 March 2021}}</ref> He was then selected in the Scotland squad for the delayed [[UEFA Euro 2020]] finals,<ref name = euros/> and scored his first international goal in a pre-tournament friendly against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref name = holland>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/football/kevin-nisbet-delighted-with-milestone-first-scotland-goal?top |title=Kevin Nisbet delighted with 'milestone' first Scotland goal |website=STV Sport |date=3 June 2021 |accessdate=4 June 2021}}</ref>

Hendry scored a crucial equaliser against the Republic of Ireland in the UEFA Nations League on 23 September 2022. Scotland went on to win the game 2–1, with [[Ryan Christie]] scoring the other Scotland goal.<ref name="ireland">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62937397|title=Scots a point from promotion after beating Ireland|last=Southwick|first=Andrew|work=BBC Sport |date=24 September 2022}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Hendry was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament, where Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> He went on to start against both [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1–1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref> and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

